yblock Health co-founder Bay Gross reached out to me to talk about a piece,=
 I was very curious.
First, because healthcare was a blind spot of mine, and it=E2=80=99s too im=
portant not to understand. Many of the next decade=E2=80=99s biggest innova=
tions, and returns, will come from healthcare.
Second, because unlike many healthcare companies, I=E2=80=99d actually hear=
d about Cityblock, and heard good things. It was born in 2017 in DUMBO, a s=
hort walk from my Brooklyn apartment, spun out of Alphabet=E2=80=99s Sidewa=
lk Labs. I have smart friends who work there. I knew it was building someth=
ing ambitious, and something in healthcare, but I just didn=E2=80=99t know =
what, exactly.=C2=A0
Third, because of the money. Cityblock has raised $462 million from very sm=
art investors, including Alphabet, Thrive, Redpoint, General Catalyst, and =
Tiger.
When I talked to Bay and co-founder Toyin Ajayi, I knew I had to write abou=
t the company. It=E2=80=99s a healthcare company that=E2=80=99s doing a lot=
 of things we talk about in Not Boring and helping a segment of the populat=
ion that=E2=80=99s often overlooked by startups.=C2=A0
